Understanding the Teen Brain

It doesn’t matter how smart teens are or how well they scored on the SAT or ACT. Good judgment isn’t something they can excel in, at least not yet.

The rational part of a teen’s brain isn’t fully developed and won’t be until age 25 or so.

In fact, recent research has found that adult and teen brains work differently. Adults think with the prefrontal cortex, the brain’s rational part. This is the part of the brain that responds to situations with good judgment and an awareness of long-term consequences. Teens process information with the amygdala. This is the emotional part.

In teens' brains, the connections between the emotional part of the brain and the decision-making center are still developing—and not always at the same rate. That’s why when teens have overwhelming emotional input, they can’t explain later what they were thinking. They weren’t thinking as much as they were feeling.

A Teen’s Brain Isn’t Fully Developed Until Age 25

Even though your teen is now as tall as you are it doesn’t mean that they have fully matured. Even though your teen may score high on the SAT or the ACT, it’s important to remember that a teen’s brain is still under development. In fact, if your child is a teenager, then you can bet that parts of their brain still need to grow and mature. >>52631363
Here we get into theory of mind. I believe the general view, at least among people who have studied the matter on a deeper level than "my pupper a good boi he just like a hoomin" is that "I did a bad thing" requires self-awareness and a capacity for abstract reasoning that animals lack. You catch your dog in the kitchen eating garbage, he tries to hide because he's afraid you're going to punish him. The dog is not operating on a human intellectual level, does not understand human concepts of right and wrong. The dog has not internalized human ideals, human cultural norms, or a human code of conduct.

Now, if we posit a sapient creature that got there by a different evolutionary pathway, well, we're talking about hypotheticals, but I would find it very plausible if an author made it a plot point in a story that we and this other species couldn't even communicate because we didn't have enough concepts in common. Science fiction authors like to write about intelligent aliens as characters, basically funny-looking people ("rubber forehead aliens"). It is much less common to write them as having fundamentally different minds, viewing the world in a fundamentally different way, making dealing with them a problem the human viewpoint character has to figure out. The best I've ever seen it done was "The Dance of the Changer and the Three," a short story from 1968 by Terry Carr. It's hard to write that way, and though skiffy fans believe themselves uncommonly intellectual, lots of them will get confused reading it. It's hard to follow. But, as an amateur author I know is fond of saying, "the right people will read it. the right people will get it."

Of course if anthros are genetically engineered in a sci-fi near-future world, all this goes out the window. And if they're in a fantasy story, having been created by a wizard, well "a wizard did it' can be used to justify anything at all the author wants to do.
